<DOC><DOCNO> AP881026-0225 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-10-26-88 0022EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   10-26 0566</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0595</SECOND><DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Kraft Inc. has advised Philip Morris Cos.Inc. to sweeten its $90 a share takeover bid to more than $110 ashare or stop pursuing its hostile offer.   Kraft Chairman John Richman's letter to Philip Morris on Tuesdayfollows Kraft's announcement of a recapitalization plan that companyofficials claimed would bring shareholders more than $110 a share incash and securities.   The recapitalization plan was announced Sunday after Kraftrejected as inadequate Philip Morris' surprise $90-a-share, or $11billion, buyout offer of last week.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Minorco SA has dropped its $4.73 billion hostilebid for Consolidated Gold Fields PLC after the British governmentsaid it would investigate the deal's effect on the market forstrategic metals.   Tuesday's developments followed a U.S. district judge's decisionin New York on Monday to issue a temporary injunction against theoffer on antitrust grounds.   Consolidated Gold Fields has resisted the buyout overture.Minorco is the Luxembourg-based investment arm of the South Africangold and diamond mining giants, Anglo American Corp. and De BeersConsolidated Mines Ltd.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The owner of Popeyes Famous Fried Chicken andBiscuits is launching a cash tender offer for Church's Fried ChickenInc. that values its fast-food chicken restaurant rival at about$290 million.   The deal announced Tuesday, if completed, would combine thesecond and third largest fast-food chicken chains in the nation. Thebiggest is Kentucky Fried Chicken, a unit of Pepsico Inc. ofPurchase, N.Y.   A. Copeland Enterprises Inc., based in New Orleans, said it wasoffering $8 a share for each of Church's 36 million shares. Church'smanagement, based in San Antonio, Texas, urged its shareholders notto tender their shares until its board could review the offer.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal court jury has rejected a $6.5billion lawsuit filed by a widow who claimed her husband died ofliver damage from taking two Tylenol products at the same time.   The U.S. District Court jury deliberated about an hour Mondaybefore rejecting the negligence suit filed by Silvia Jauchler, whosehusband Maurice died last year.   Johnson andamp; Johnson attorney Robert E. Christiansen said Tylenoldid not cause the dead man's problem and that the company wasgrateful for the jury's verdict.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Mobil Corp. and Chevron Corp. each have reported double-digitthird quarter profit gains, while profits at Texaco Inc. andPhillips Petroleum Co. more than doubled in the latest period.   Meanwhile, Shell Oil Co., Sun Co. and Amerada Hess Corp. eachreported sharp declines Tuesday in their net earnings due partly todeclining crude oil prices.   The larger oil companies said earnings were both hurt and helpedby falling crude prices. Lower costs for the raw product contributedto higher profit margins in refining and marketing operations buteroded gains in exploration and production.</TEXT><DATELINE>WHEELING, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A new contract with the UnitedSteelworkers union is one of the major obstacles asWheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. prepares to present itsreorganization plan to federal bankruptcy court.   Company President and Chief Executive Officer WilliamScharffenberger said Tuesday that negotiating an equitable laboragreement ``is the single most important task still before us.''   Scharffenberger said the next contract between management andworkers will determine whether Wheeling-Pittsburgh can compete inthe global steel economy after emerging from bankruptcy.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>